WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil.

4
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
And I'm Georgie.

5
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Some people remember their school days as the best time of their lives.

6
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.000
For others, it was the worst.

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Did you enjoy school Georgie?

8
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:27.000
Most of the time, yes, but there was one thing I didn't like.

9
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.000
The school rules.

10
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Luckily, that's not a problem for pupils at the Bamboo School in Thailand.

11
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Because they're the children, not the teachers, make the rules.

12
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
Children at the Bamboo School are responsible for every part of running the school.

13
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.000
From buying food for the kitchens to disciplining fellow students, and even hiring new staff,

14
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
it's a school run by students for students.

15
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Yes, in this program we'll be hearing about the Bamboo School.

16
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
A unique school whether children call the shots.

17
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.000
They have the power to make the decisions.

18
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:13.000
We'll also be learning some useful new vocabulary, and before you ask Phil, yes, the Bamboo School really is made of bamboo.

19
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Sounds good, Georgie.

20
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:18.000
But first, I have a question for you.

21
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:24.000
The Bamboo School is a private school for poor children who can't afford school fees.

22
00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Bamboo School children get educated for free, but have to do something in return.

23
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.000
But what?

24
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Is it a teach lessons?

25
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
B, plant trees, or C, learning English?

26
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:44.000
I guess they have to learn English.

27
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
Okay, Georgie. I'll reveal the answer at the end of the program.

28
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
The idea behind the Bamboo School is simple.

29
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Teaching children responsibility by letting them run their own school.

30
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:03.000
The school doesn't employ cooks, gardeners, or cleaners, it's all done by the pupils.

31
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Twice a week, children go to the vegetable market with a school officer, and buy food for all 150 students.

32
00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:17.000
The prices are then carefully checked by other students like Nuneem, who manages the food accounts.

33
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:24.000
Here's Nuneem speaking with William Cramer, reporter for BBC World Service program, people fixing the world.

34
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
I am interested in accounting to begin with, so I get excited by it.

35
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.000
When I actually get to do it, I enjoy the lot, since we are doing the actual job.

36
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:40.000
With this hands-on experience, we see the schools real spending and the things we purchased.

37
00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:47.000
So you went to a local school before, just in this area, what are the differences between that school and this school?

38
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:54.000
My old school was like this. It was just classes and then home.

39
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:01.000
Here I get to try so many things, can real-world experience and work on my leadership skills with my friends.

40
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
And never had these opportunities before, and the school has been amazing.

41
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Nuneem says shopping at the market is a hands-on experience. She's actively involved in doing something practical, rather than getting someone else to do it.

42
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:20.000
She enjoys managing the food accounts because it's real-world experience.

43
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:28.000
The phrase real-world describes how the world works in reality, rather than someone's idea of it, which might be unrealistic.

44
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.000
Children at the bamboo school get opportunities to try something new and different outside the classroom,

45
00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
increasing the chances they'll find something they're really good at.

46
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Of course, there are some adults. Every school needs teachers, but what's special is how children are trusted and respond positively to that trust.

47
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Here's a report of William Cramer, again, speaking with Myra Anubi for BBC World Service Program, people fixing the world.

48
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:08.000
So just to be clear, it seems like the grown-ups are still in charge in the classrooms, but outside it's a kids who run stuff.

49
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Yeah, I think that's broadly right. And I think one of the things that's interesting about this school is it manages to be quite conventional in some ways and really innovative, even radical in others.

50
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:31.000
At the bamboo school, the grown-ups, another word for adults, are still in charge in the classroom, but it's the kids or children who run everything.

51
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:37.000
It's a radical idea and means that besides lessons, there's lots of work to be done.

52
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Children do two hours of community service. That's work that is done without pay to help people in the community every week.

53
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Anyway, I think it's time to reveal the answer to your question.

54
00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:56.000
Yes, we just heard that kids go to the bamboo school for free, but do something in return. But what?

55
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Georgie guessed it was learning English, which was the wrong answer I'm afraid. In fact, pupils at the school have to plant trees.

56
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:10.000
400 of them every year.

57
00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Right, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned from this program about a school where the kids or children call the shots.

58
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:22.000
A phrase meaning have the power to make the important decisions.

59
00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:32.000
Hands on experience means being actively involved in doing something practical, rather than just talking about it or getting someone else to do it.

60
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:42.000
The phrase real world is used to describe how the world really is, rather than someone's idea of it, which may be unrealistic or untypical.

61
00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:48.000
A grown-up is an informal word for an adult, and a kid is an informal word for a child.

62
00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:55.000
And finally, community service is work that is done without pay to help people in a community.

63
00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember to join us again next time for more trending topics and useful vocabulary here at six minute English. Goodbye for now.
